{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486951"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:51:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:51:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"216"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/216"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.03,0.08,0.31,0.38]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"216"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76323"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/216"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"216"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61832"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"256"},{"type":"tags","id":"9078"},{"type":"tags","id":"9528"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"506"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4378"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76323"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 69-year-old woman presents with a four week history of anorexia and weight loss. Over the last three days she had become jaundiced, with dark urine and pale stools. She has no other symptoms. She had recently returned from a holiday in Bali and had been taking doxycycline for prevention of malaria. Apart from the jaundice, physical examination is unremarkable. The liver function test results are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAspartate aminotransferase (AST) 294 (\u0026lt;35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlanine aminotransferase (ALT) 361 U/L (\u0026lt;35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlkaline phosphatase (ALP) 1914 U/L (25-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGamma glutamyl transferase (GGT) 859 U/L (\u0026lt;50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBilirubin 293 \u00b5mol/L (\u0026lt;20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum albumin 31 g/L (32-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is ultimately going to be of the most value?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transabdominal ultrasound","Stool culture","Thick blood film for parasites","Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP)","Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP)"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe progressive picture of obstructive jaundice over a subacute timeframe illustrated in this case raises concern for a malignant obstructing lesion of the biliary tree such as carcinoma of the head of the pancreas. The predominant derangement of cholestatic liver enzymes (ALP and GGT) also suggests a biliary aetiology to the hyperbilirubinaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn obstructing lesion may be demonstrated on transabdominal ultrasound or CT, and one of these is indeed likely to be the initial investigation. However, \u003Cstrong\u003EERCP\u003C/strong\u003E not only enables delineation of the biliary tree and detailed assessment of the site of obstruction, but also enables sampling of tissue for histopathology and stenting to relieve the obstruction. As such, ERCP tends to be the procedure of choice following initial investigations. MRCP is generally reserved for cases in which ERCP is contraindicated or fails, therapeutic intervention is unlikely to be needed, or the patient opts for non-invasive imaging; standard contraindications to MRI imaging apply.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEmerging techniques based on endoscopic ultrasound (EUS) are increasingly deployed for tissue sampling or bile diversion, particularly when ERCP is unsuccessful.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["ERCP has both diagnostic and therapeutic value in the workup of obstructive jaundice"],"references":["Fargo MV, Grogan SP, Saguil A. Evaluation of Jaundice in Adults. Am Fam Physician. 2017 Feb 1;95(3):164-168. PMID: 28145671. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28145671/","Zar S, Kohoutov\u00e1 D, Bure\u0161 J. Pancreatic Adenocarcinoma: Epidemiology, Role of EUS in Diagnosis, Role of ERCP, Endoscopic Palliation. Acta Medica (Hradec Kralove). 2019;62(4):131-136. doi: 10.14712/18059694.2020.1. PMID: 32036844. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32036844/","Kaltenthaler EC, Walters SJ, Chilcott J, Blakeborough A, Vergel YB, Thomas S. MRCP compared to diagnostic ERCP for diagnosis when biliary obstruction is suspected: a systematic review. BMC Med Imaging. 2006 Aug 14;6:9. doi: 10.1186/1471-2342-6-9. PMID: 16907974; PMCID: PMC1579209.  Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16907974/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61832"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"216"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61832"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T05:57:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T05:57:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"216"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76323"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Sur